---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section id="capabilities" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
        <span class="text-neutral-600">04</span> The fills
      </p>
      <h2
        class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        What a meta-harness does
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
        Take the two problems in order. A meta-harness solves each one the way a
        meta-framework solved routing and rendering: it does the plumbing for
        you, once, in a way that transfers.
      </p>
    </div>

    <article class="mt-16 grid items-center gap-12 border-t border-neutral-900 pt-14 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-sm text-neutral-600">01</span>
          <h3
            class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-3xl"
          >
            Cross-repo work
          </h3>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          <p>
            The meta-harness knows what a repository is, and how repos relate. So
            it provisions the repos you need, each on the correct branch, sets up
            the worktrees, and gets the agents running side by side. You do not
            touch any of it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Then it treats a code change as its own object, distinct from a pull
            request, because one change can span several repos and several PRs.
            It <mark>coordinates the change across all of them</mark> and opens
            the PRs so they land together. The whole choreography you were doing
            by hand becomes a single thing the meta-harness runs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder label="RepositoryGraph island" ratio="aspect-[4/3]" />
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="mt-16 grid items-center gap-12 border-t border-neutral-900 pt-14 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="lg:order-first">
        <VizPlaceholder label="SessionNetwork island" ratio="aspect-[4/3]" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline gap-3">
          <span class="font-mono text-sm text-neutral-600">02</span>
          <h3
            class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-3xl"
          >
            Sessions
          </h3>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          <p>
            The session with all its reasoning stops being a file on your laptop.
            It is captured automatically and shared across the organization, so
            it is reachable by anyone, not just you, not just this machine.
          </p>
          <p>
            More than stored, sessions are connected into a graph, because work
            is almost always built on other work. So the next time you come
            around to that area, the agent <mark>finds and references the
            session that touched it</mark>, pulls in what was decided and why,
            and starts from there instead of from scratch. The reasoning you were
            afraid of losing is now the context the next session begins with.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>
